Based on your domain map, here are example queries for each agent:

**Sales agent**
- "What was our total revenue this year?"
- "Which region has the highest sales?"
- "What is our current win rate?"
- "Show me all deals in negotiation stage"
- "Which deal has the highest probability of closing?"
- "How did Q3 revenue compare to target?"

**Inventory agent**
- "Which products are below reorder point?"
- "What is our total inventory value?"
- "Which category has the highest turnover rate?"
- "Show me all SKUs with low stock alerts"
- "What is the unit cost of Gadget X?"
- "Which product needs to be reordered urgently?"

**Finance agent**
- "What is our profit margin this year?"
- "Which department is over budget?"
- "Show me the expense breakdown"
- "What were total expenses in March?"
- "How does actual spending compare to budget in Engineering?"
- "What is our net profit this quarter?"

**HR agent**
- "How many employees do we have in total?"
- "Which department has the most headcount?"
- "What is our annual turnover rate?"
- "How many open positions do we have?"
- "Show me hiring trends for the last 6 months"
- "What is the average employee tenure?"

**General agent** (cross-domain)
- "Give me a full company health summary"
- "Compare revenue growth vs headcount growth"
- "Are we profitable enough to hire more people?"
- "What are the biggest risks across all departments?"
- "How is the company performing overall?"

---

The **general agent** queries are the most powerful ones — they force the orchestrator to synthesize insights across all four domains at once, which is the core value of a multi-agent system.